public_description: Dear Elected Official(s), Public Servant(s), and City/State Employees: I am an owner at Latitude, located at 3605-3665 Ash Street just north of the 94 freeway at Home Avenue in 92105.  There are a growing number of homeless encampments surrounding our community and encroaching upon it, both on city owned property, CalTrans property, and our own private property via breached fences securing the freeway and riverbed area.  In light of the terrible wildfires in Los Angeles, and considering our own history of fires started by these encampments, which including recently are still commonplace, I am tremendously concerned about the safety of my person and my property.  I understand many reports and calls have been made to the relevant outlets and authorities without resolve. We need action before a tragedy occurs. This is a 100% preventable risk, similar to the loss of homes in the recent floods nearby due to the city?s inaction at clearing encampments which ultimately blocked flood channels.

Visible in the encampment was sleeping bag, folded blankets, duffle bag/luggage, and a collapsed Easy Up shade structure.  Please work to relocate the person(s) occupying this space, as fire danger from campfire is of high concern in this wilderness canyon area.  Thank you.

WE always get resolutions that say "moved 1/10th of a mile" but in reality, the cars are still there and on the cul de sac which is not even 1/10th of a mile in length so I have no idea what they mean. Maybe this is due to the fact that the car owners  are extremely aggressive and intimidating. We are filing one more report in case anyone cares enough to help. Most of the neighbors are elderly and they are not about to confront anyone, so I am filing this report in the name of us all. Please help! At least let them know that they cannot just park their cars there and just leave them there! We all pay taxes! It's inconsiderate! They also double park every single day, ( see pic)- they own about 16 cars and many people reside in their house.

public_description: There is a large single encampment in the bushes along a bike trail in Mission Valley Preserve.  I had reported the encampment a couple of months ago and got a reply that you were waiting on grant funding from the state (specifically for the San Diego River area) to remove encampments.  Since then, no action has been taken.  The encampment has grown in size now with a LOT of debris, bushes have been cut to make more room for the dweller (bushes that are supposed to be Preserved in a Preserve), and the camper is lighting cooking fires.  If the encampment had been removed when I first reported it, it would have been a small task.  Now the task has grown more complex.  To reach the camp, park at the little league field on the North side of I-8 and just West of the Best Western Inn.  Take the small paved access road west toward Cottonwood Grove Park (see pic).  Take the first trail on the right, which is marked by a small wood rail fence (see pic).  The tent is a short distance on the left of the trail (see pics)

public_description: Homeless encampment at the Fairmount end of the canyon that runs downward west to east between Van Dyke Ave. and Fairmount.  There is NO ADDRESS OR STRUCTURE directly on this dirt trail where the encampment is located. The Van Dyke opening of the dirt path that runs down to Fairmont is located just south of 4567 Van Dyke Ave, between two private residences. People on foot or with bicycles, carrying big plastic sacks most likely filled with clothes and camp supplies have frequently been observed - for years - walking down the trail to the encampment. Latest observation was today, 4/27, late morning - man with a black plastic sack walking a bike into the canyon from Van Dyke entrance.  Neighbors have also reported spotting occasional campfires there. This situation is a huge danger, as the overgrown brush in the canyon is extremely dry and therefore creates chance of fires. There is no residence, therefore no address, at this location. Occasionally it is possible to see tents from Fairmont southbound.

public_description: I own a home on E. Mountain View, a little south of Adams Ave. We have a fire hydrant on the corner with an extension that is being used by large trucks to refill their water tanks. These trucks, some as big as my house, pull up to the hydrant at all hours of the day and night. I have heard their massive engines idling outside my home, and literally shaking the walls at midnight, 3 AM and 4 AM. They also undertake this 20-minute procedure during the day. At least 10 people live in the apartment building next to the fire hydrant who also experience these disturbances, as well as my neighbors in other nearby residences. There are fire hydrants nearby that are not close to homes and apartments. The one on Cherokee outside the now-closed RiteAid is available as well as the one on the next block, 36th Street, next to Vons. These would easier for major trucks to access and give us some peace. Thank you.
